  <article class="article">
    <p class="eyebrow">Guide</p>
    <h1>How to Extract Tables from a PDF to Excel</h1>
    <p>PDFs are great for sharing reports, but awkward when you need the table data behind them. The fastest path is to extract the table structure directly and export it to XLSX.</p>
    <h2>Start with the PDF type</h2>
    <p>If you can select table text in your PDF viewer, the file is text-based and a table extractor can often read rows and columns. If the page is a scan or photo, you need OCR first.</p>
    <h2>Use a table-focused converter</h2>
    <p>A full PDF to Excel converter tries to recreate the page. A table extractor focuses on the data grid, which is usually what you need for analysis.</p>
    <h2>Review the result</h2>
    <p>Always check headers, merged cells, totals, and page breaks before using the spreadsheet in production work.</p>
    <p class="callout">Try the free converter on the main PDF Table to Excel page for text-based PDFs.</p>
  </article>
